webpackJsonp([68386835970074],{373:function(e,a){e.exports={data:{site:{siteMetadata:{title:"Mathias Schilling - Just another paper cut survivor and software engineer",author:"Mathias Schilling"}},markdownRemark:{id:"/home/mathias/dev/com.matchilling.www/src/pages/article/2017-11-16-call-for-collaboration/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>\n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 69.75308641975309%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/png;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;"\n        alt="Brexit start-up screen"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/brexit-screenshot-ec1612d63a5cf06db2aed58f3f686bd3-3ff5c.png"\n        srcset="/static/brexit-screenshot-ec1612d63a5cf06db2aed58f3f686bd3-5d15a.png 200w,\n/static/brexit-screenshot-ec1612d63a5cf06db2aed58f3f686bd3-645cb.png 400w,\n/static/brexit-screenshot-ec1612d63a5cf06db2aed58f3f686bd3-3ff5c.png 800w,\n/static/brexit-screenshot-ec1612d63a5cf06db2aed58f3f686bd3-4954a.png 972w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  </p>\n<h2>TL;DR Abstract</h2>\n<h1>Start learning prolog</h1>\n<p>I’m a language addict ~ I love learning new languages, spoken ones and those ones you can do funny things in a computer with. As part of a MSc degree I’ve picked the “Programming Paradigms and Languages” module offered by Birkbeck University of London, which was nicely delivered by Keith Mannock and Trevor Fenner. The main aim of the module was to enable students to understand the key differences between various programming paradigms and the applicability of these paradigms to different programming problems.\nThis module was the reason why I felt in love with <code>prolog</code>,  a logic programming language which is heavily used in computational linguistics and artificial intelligence in general. As part of the practical coursework I’ve started working on “Brexit”, a text adventure for the command line</p>\n<p>From The Pragmatic Programmer, Tip #8 “Invest Regularly in Your Knowledge Portfolio”:\nLearn at least one new language every year. Different languages solve the same problems in different ways. By learning several different approaches, you can help broaden your thinking and avoid getting stuck in a rut. Additionally, learning many languages is far easier now, thanks to the wealth of freely available software on the Internet</p>\n<h2>Preface</h2>\n<p>In May this year I found myself playing around with <a href="http://www.swi-prolog.org/"><code>prolog</code></a>, a logical programming language which later I fell in love with. I was thinking about a small project to continue my studies and to dive deeper in to the language. I live in the United Kingdom and at that time the media was dominated by the country’s plan to withdrawal from the European Union, so I thought creating kind of a political text adventure with prolog could be something entertaining but at the same time informative.</p>\n<p>As time has past and I didn’t make as much progress as I would have wished, I thought probably <a href="https://github.com/matchilling/brexit">open sourcing</a> and making it a collaborative project could be interesting for others who would like to start learning about <a href="https://bernardopires.com/2013/10/try-logic-programming-a-gentle-introduction-to-prolog/">logical programming</a> as well.</p>\n<p><strong>So this is a call for collaboration</strong>!</p>\n<h2>Current state</h2>\n<h3>BREXIT - A !serious adventure for the Ununited Kingdom</h3>\n<h2>Part I - Road to Brexit</h2>\n<p>In the first part of this neverending story you will lead the UK from the Post-Cameron-Era to the beginning of the Brexit negotiations. The goal is to trigger the article 50 in Brussels.</p>\n<h2>Usage</h2>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-sh"><code># Use the shell start-up script,\n$ ./bin/brexit</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-prolog"><code><span class="token operator">:-</span> <span class="token punctuation">[</span><span class="token string">&apos;src/brexit&apos;</span><span class="token punctuation">]</span><span class="token operator">.</span>\n</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h3>Available commands</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><code>start.</code>: start a new game</li>\n<li><code>n. s. e. w.</code>: go in that direction</li>\n<li><code>look.</code>: look around</li>\n<li><code>help.</code>: show help message</li>\n<li><code>version.</code>: show game version information</li>\n<li><code>quit.</code>: end the game and quit</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>References</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://github.com/matchilling/brexit">https://github.com/matchilling/brexit</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-03-20/brexit-timeline-from-eu-referendum-to-theresa-may-and-article-50">https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-03-20/brexit-timeline-from-eu-referendum-to-theresa-may-and-article-50</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p><img src="https://thepracticaldev.s3.amazonaws.com/i/mk1b88gjdgztesrcdld8.gif" alt="Happy Brexit"></p>\n<img class="emoji-icon" data-icon="emoji-v" style="display: inline; margin: 0; position: relative; top: 5px; width: 25px" src="data:image/png;base64, ">',frontmatter:{date:"16 November, 2017",path:"/call-for-collaboration/",tags:"game, open source, programming language paradigms, prolog, logic programming",title:"Call for collaboration"}}},pathContext:{path:"/call-for-collaboration/",_PARENT:"SOURCE"}}}});
